76561198077987627,Recommended,329430,15885655,"Posted: 18 May, 2015",all,Jonathan Taylor Thomas,"While I support everyone's cause to end developers with the $$ in their eyes, this is clearly not the right title to be doing it on and the people doing so are misinformed.TL;DR - Developers (who made the game) have no control over the business practice as this still is a Microsoft-published/controlled title. It's a stretch that Microsoft even let this game go on Steam, so don't expect any official support beyond what was already offered. Undead Labs aren't accountable here. This is the remaster of a previously 2-gig sized game, and you are getting out of it what you are willing to pay for it.I'm sitting here reading these ""most helpful"" reviews from people with much, much less than even 5 hours in the game (a lot of them ironically saying they 'haven't seen anything different or new content-wise yet'), while reviews that are simply people saying they can't start the game (likely because their graphics setup doesn't support Dx11/isn't updated) somehow got upvoted to the most helpful page.Meanwhile, it doesn't take much to see the shameless squad of review-skewers operating out of the vow to upvote every single negative post no matter how meaningless it is and downvote the opposite, so right now it's pretty hard to view an actual, thought-out review of this game (Obviously, don't pretend I'm somehow 'unbiased' or 'more correct' in this situation). I'm going to predict that the amount of people who downvote this post within the next several hours will prove those previous statements (update - accumulation of 247/1053 as of Oct. 5th 2016).For further thought material: For a brisk while post-release, critic reviews on Metacritic for this game were definitely positive, and the problems those reviews mainly have with the game are more about a lack of polish and the fact that it wasn't a complete 'overhaul' like they hoped for, rather than it being a bad purchase or a bad game. Of course, by now, even some of those are under the impression that those ""darn corrupt devs"" made this to rob us thanks to the keyboard-activism.The issue with the talk of business practice is how obvious it is that nobody is actually looking into the validity of what they are saying - Undead Labs is not in control of the business practice. They are the dev team, it is their concept and ideas that built it, but ultimately, they signed it away to Microsoft for publishing with the XBLA system back in the 360's development stage.Before you assume that it's their fault anyways - remember that the XBLA program exists for small dev teams to have a place to release their game to the console market, and rules must be followed and UL would not have had any choice in the matter (being as small as they were with no resources at the time). Nobody knew the game was going to succeed how it did.What does this mean? Well, it certainly doesn't mean that Undead Labs even had the authority to ""screw the customers"" if they wanted to (which anyone with half a brain for PR can assume that they didn't). Rather that this is the PC port for theXbox Oneversion of the game, which sold for the simple reason that SOD otherwise did not exist on current (XB1) gen consoles at the time. Undead Labs has also stated that they cannot update the port without the go-ahead from Microsoft, which does not care about the PC port in terms of promoting their console-heavyexclusive title State of Decay.Now, if you actually care about what's in the game and how it compares to the last version, here is actually new content-wise in YOSE:-New knife-combat (which comes with a bunch of nice badass moves) (One of the bigger changes in the game)-New difficulty arch for Breakdown that extends far beyond the previous 12 levels.-30 minutes of new music-The amount of cars has more than doubled (although most of these come from new variants of already-existing vehicles. There is a classic 80's sedan, SUV, a non-customized version of the modern muscle car, some new tuners, a new classic muscle car and a bunch of new colors and variants for all of them.)-Some balance and physics tweaks-Fleshed out car repair features-New facility options (you can now do stuff like make coffee and convert ammo and stuff like that)-A bunch of new guns-A new type of mission (which is acts as a really nice reward occasionally in breakdown)-New Breakdown Heroes/survivors (including a returning-player bonus)(Milo Eldrige is an example of a new generic survivor for those misinformed souls that think Gurubani is the only change).-Slightly sharper graphics and frame rate (Not even close to a big change)-New visual ground effects, actual fog, etcKNOW WHAT YOU ARE BUYING. THIS IS PROBABLY NOT WORTH 30$ FOR PEOPLE WHO ALREADY HAVE THE GAME.ON THE CONTRARY, IF YOU DO NOT OWN THE ORIGINAL STATE OF DECAY, YOU AREN'T EVEN PART OF THE DEMOGRAPHIC THAT COULD CLAIM TO BE CHEATED. DON'T EXPECT THE REMASTER OF A 2GB GAME TO OPERATE LIKE A 30GB AAA GAME.If you are a new buyer to the series, then yah, buy this. State of Decay is a great game, and this is definitely the better version to get. There is more content, a bunch of smaller features the previous did not have, more community support for it.Despite the generic review claiming the game is 'broken' with 'broken features', the game is far from unplayable. The majority of bugs are physics flaws and bugs are definitely not something the game is bad with.Aside from that, if you are angry about the game not getting enough attention, you can blame MS for trying to make this a cash grab. The developers - who are very attentive to the community on the website - can't even do a DLC until the publishers ask for it. I'm not trying to baselessly shift blame, that is literally what one of the developers said when answering a community suggestion (https://forums.undeadlabs.com/threads/the-guns.27815/page-281). Keep in mind that in that same thread the developer can be quoted as saying that something new might just be in the works as well for the game."
