,Recommended,329430,32628560,Posted: 21 June,all,bihlbo,"YOSE vs. Original: Better graphics, not much else.SoD either version is a really fun zombie beat-em-up with lots of driving, looting, and fighting. The base building aspects are very simple and contribute little to the game. For the most part, this game is best as a quick-session ""let's see if I can't find some goodies and kill some things"" game. In fact, playing for more than an hour or so is probably not the best idea, as the game's new things to throw at you become stale after about that long. It uses a mix of real and game time to progress things while you're not playing, meaning it rewards you for playing a little every day instead of long play sessions. Combat is great fun, forcing you to come up with new strategies as the game gets more difficult. Your main enemy is actually scarcity more than it is the monstrous zeds, which are more of an obstacle than anything since you can  never truly win against them.SoD is not a perfect game at all. Certainly some of the features seem half-baked. There are only two settings to explore, then memorize and master, and the lack of anything new to see can get stale. Your impact on the setting is very limited, and fleeting. The original game's story is kinda meh, Lifeline's is better, and Breakdown doesn't have a story.However, I have a hard time finding a better game to fill the role that SoD fills, as a simple, short-session, couch sitter."
