,Not Recommended,329430,32004937,Posted: 27 May,all,C-zom,"Pros:*Early game melee*Initial immersion factor*Voice Acting + Quantity of characters*Weapon variety*Driving is decent*Fun gameplay loop of loot, build, loot, build.Cons:*Significant level of low polish, including numerous launch/crash/freeze hangups in Breakdown.*Low fidelity graphics feel like Cryengine 3 permanently set to low settings. Most jarring sin is vegetation, grass, ground textures and LOD distance even on Ultra + SweetFX mods.*Breakdown being a recycling DLC was a poor idea to feign a difficulty mode, and takes too long to reach meaningful heights. You'll easily put 4-8 hours into the same map before you reach Level 5 or 6, when the game actually becomes difficult and harrowing.*Dead open world*No real sense of mid or end game*No meta events or map control or dynamic weather or anything of the sort.*Doesn't bring you down to earth. Your own personal hunger, sickness, health, morale, or all those traits the game showcases (poet, builder, musician, etc) mean absolutely nothing. NPC's do not interact with each other much at all.I originally bought State of Decay on the 360 and enjoyed it for what it was then. The original PC port actually turned out to be a bit more stable than this combined release, but more on that later. Ultimately you might be asking: What is YOSE? Why should this game interest me, there are a million zombie sims out there.To start with the positives, the gameplay loop in Decay is rewarding. You find or start a small community in one of a few predetermined ""start options"" you can roam around on the map and find. From there you need to loot buildings of various size and complexity to find rucksacks full of either food, ammo, supplies, or some forth income that is illuding me at the moment. This is your base building and maintenance currency which you use to construct/upgrade tiers of modules like sleeping room (more survivors) medical bay (faster health regen on chars you're not using) and so on and so forth. Killing zombies is mostly rewarding at the earlier levels with a pretty immersive melee engine, but is -- to me -- murked completely at higher levels when you become a crowd controller similar to Dead Rising.You can equip 2h saws and spin to win, you can one hit kill enemies with fast light handed weapons and chain combo, etc. I found the combat most immersive when dodging, hitting, and running while managing stamina to be the most fun. At higher level characters, which is easy enough to do in one or two in game days, you become a killing machine. Janky animations, but meaty impact helps to level out the combat. Ranged is awful, I have nothing else to say there.Zombies tend to spawn around you in a shell, out of view, rather than say roaming the map in swarms or migrating. The lack of any established a-life tends to bring down immersion since you can clear a house, go to the top floor, come back down and it's full of zombies again. This happens a lot.Because of this, base attacks are predetermined ""horde"" events that spawn out of thin air and rush your defenses. This is fun, at first, but as you tier up you won't even notice or care as your snipers will make swift work of things.There is not much of a mid or end game to speak of. There are no dynamic events, military incursions, zombie migrations, roaming survivor bands like you just fighting and looting, special weather or sickness events, etc. The big world is really static and tends to have a small center of gravity -- you. Enemies spawn when you're there, stuff is raided when you're around, ""Defense"" missions for outposts only happen when you can help, etc. The game uses missions and gametokens (cryengine stuff) to feign a sense of dynamics. In reality, the game stays put until it can pull your hair to do something close by.Breakdown Endgame is just getting in an RV, reloading the entire map and it adds mutators to enemy count/strength/ and loot amount/scarcity. That's it. Ultimately, SoD is a decent looters beat em' up with a faint semblance of an open world. It is worth it on sale for $10 or below, but it isn't going to be the diehard zombie sandbox you were hoping for. It is too detached from itself, too player centered, too easy and has a strange dichotomy between corny Dead Rising combat and struggle-to-survive (implied, anyway) basebuilding."
