,Recommended,329430,28193555,"Posted: 4 December, 2016",all,Adam,"ORIGINAL REVIEW / TL;DR:Best zombie game on the market. All it needs is co-op, and we're getting that with State of Decay 2.NEW REVIEW:I didn't expect this to become the top review, so I'm rewriting this review...First off, many of the negative reviews for this game are those who bought SoD before YOSE came out. I agree with these negative reviewers that this is a sham deal on the publisher's part making people pay for a repackaging of the game. YOSE is essentially SoD with all the DLCs and improved graphics, so if I had bought SoD before YOSE came out, I'd be upset too.State of Decay is certainly a different type of zombie game, as it is one that you can play at your own pace and unlike many other zombie games you actually work to try to form a civilization out of the apocalypse. I haven't played every single zombie game, but I've played ones like L4D, CoD Zombies, The Walking Dead, DayZ, 7 Days to Die. SoD is definitely my favorite out of these because it couples an open world with characters that have personalities that can grow onto you. So I guess you could call this game a cross between the Walking Dead and DayZ.Another thing that makes this game more interesting is character death. Once a character dies in a playthrough, they stay dead for good. This has resulted in me deleting my save at one point because my best character got killed in an attack. It certainly changes the dynamic of the game, and even the characters who remain alive address the death of a character.The game is very well developed mechanically. I never ran into any game breaking glitches during my first playthrough, if any glitches at all, honestly. The game is good on this aspect, although the game still has a bit to be desired in the graphics department. I don't mind that seeing as this game is about two years old and never saw a physical release until YOSE released on Xbox One.Now for actual gameplay:In short, the game is fun to play. Melee combat (which is the majority of what you'll be doing in SoD) flows very smoothly, with fluid hacking, slashing, and swinging animations. It doesn't look like you're swinging at air when you're trying to fight off zombies. Shooting is also a lot of fun. The reload times are pretty realistic (meaning they're not very fast). This can make or break the game for you, depending on who you are, but I personally love it. You also can't spray everywhere with automatic weapons and hit your targets like you can in other shooters. I think the devs did a great job overall with combat.Driving is okay, I wish the vehicles were a bit faster/more durable than they are. Also on vehicles, they can't be modded with things like bullbars, armor, etc. Although the driving in game isn't great, it isn't unbearable either. It works well for what it is, and running over a horde of zombies is always a blast.Scavenging is also a lot of fun. Essentially, you comb through buildings, landmarks, etc. for supplies to bring back to your settlement. The types of supplies vary (food, medicine, ammo, etc.) When you find supplies, you can only carry one rucksack-full at a time, so it's always best to bring a vehicle with you and possible other people from your settlement to scavenge with you. Supplies also don't respawn in the buildings you scavenge as far as I know, so you can play at your own pace as long as you can find supplies. I'm sure anyone can finish the game before they run out of places to loot so this isn't really a problem.The single complaint I have about this game is that there's no multiplayer, but that doesn't really stop me from having a lot of fun with this game. It has so much replay value. Co-op will be coming in SoD 2, though.I barely scratched the surface of this game while writing this, there is so much more to this game than what I went over. It is certainly worth full price in my mind, so give it a go. Definitely buy it if you see it on sale, though. You won't regret it. 9.5/10."
