,Recommended,329430,30506742,Posted: 14 March,all,Strange,"Whenever I attempt to describe State of Decay to people who have never played the game, I find myself describing the game I want State of Decay to be--and the game that Undead Labs attempted to craft--more than the game that State of Decay actually is. State of Decay wants to be many games--chief among them the first video game to properly capture the community survival elements of a Dawn of the Dead film in mechanical terms (as opposed to the narrative terms of Telltale's The Walking Dead)--and, at its best moments, it creates a sense of community, tension, and character agency matched by few of its peers. But for each moment of spontaneous, unscripted story wonder that State of Decay generates, it is also one glitch, bug, or broken feature away from drawing you completely out of its experience.THE GOOD- Creates legitimate sense of community among your group of survivors-  Permadeath adds tangible tension to every outing- Building up base & team feels like a less pessimistic George Romero filmTHE BAD- Omnipresent bugs ranging from humorous to game-breaking- Controls lack finesse for more hectic action sequences- Multiple modes of play fail to meaningfully feed back into one another- World lacks distinct sense of placeIn my opinion, I give this a 6 out of 10."
