76561197998490461,Not Recommended,329430,30522920,Posted: 15 March,all,cheep crybabby hatter,"I have no illusions about how I'd survive in a zombie apocalypse. I'm not the fastest, the most prepared, the most agile, or the most sensible. The uncertainty of such a dangerous, nomadic lifestyle, where vital resources could simply not exist wherever you choose to go; I find it demotivating, a response that would prove deadly. But, in spite of this, I've always had a fascination with zombie survival games (i.e. not the arcadey shmups like Resident Evil 4 or Bulletstorm). There's something about that delicate balance between horror, stealth, action based combat, strategic base building, economic management, and curshingly bleak drama to be found in a deadly, crumbling world, all wrapped up in an emergent, player-driven story. It's a heady 7-ball juggling act that many attempt but few do well. Often the game can only juggle one or two at a time. Often, some balls are just dropped altogether.Make no bones about it, State of Decay is brilliant. I've played my share of zombie survival games, and just about every single one of them has left me slightly unfulfilled, thinking about the potential the genre has to be great. And, when I do, State of Decay is the game I keep asking for.With the exception of perhaps the drama, State of Decay juggles all the balls with aplomb. You are an ordinary person, on holiday with a friend, when zombies strike. After a small tutorial, you're then basically free to explore the massive area, looting resources, building outposts that net you resources, finding people to help (or do missions for), or just to walk around killing zombies. You can approach the zombies as stealthily as you want, either by sneaking up to them and smashing their brains on nearby objects, shoot at them with the firearms of your choice, by just running away, or any combination in between. Zombies will naturally spawn in various locations, and there are no progammed jump scares, so the horror is completely organic.You also are only human, so after enought time and exertion, your character will become fatigued, which lowers maximum fatiue. That's when you have to return to base to rest. You can then talk to another NPC to take them out on a mission, or even convince them to join you on a scavenging hunt. The base can be upgraded using scavenged materials, which affords a variety of benefits. Bases have running costs too, so the scavenged materials must address these needs. Plus, killing zombies affords benefits to your base, as it naturally should; the fewer zombies around, the less damage they'll do to the base and its morale.On top of all this, there is a story, and missions for you to complete. So there is drama, although not all of it emergent. It's a delicate balance between story-driven purpose and sandboxed fun. There's plenty of reward for exploring and doing your own thing, but at the same time, you don't feel like it's all pointless.As the big red thumbs down indicates, after such glowing sentiments, there is a big ugly ""but"" coming. BUT, as much as State of Decay expertly realises some high ambitions, and as much as it is the game I keep asking for, I'm not sure if it's the game I want to play. The problem is that surviving in State of Decay feels a little bit too like the real thing (obviously I don't mean ""the real thing"" literally!).First and foremost, there's State of Decay's most controversial feature: real time passing changes things in game. Remember when I talked about the running costs of bases? They subtract from your base's total every 24 hours IRL. It's also not the only thing that changes IRL. I came back to a game I had stopped playing, and found that several of my people were either dead or missing, which is potentially a big problem. Bases also chew up building materials like nothing else, which is essential for various upgrades.This ties into my second gripe, which is that resources are more or less finite. Once a place is looted, it doesn't magically spawn new resources. With certain upgrades, it's possible to convert certain resources into others (e.g. food into fuel, by a process of making biodiesel), but other resources (such as building materials) cannot be manufactured or converted at all. So, it is possible to arrive at a situation, after many hours of play, where you no longer have access to any building materials. Plus, when a base can't cover its running cost in materials, this causes a very large hit to the morale, which can cause people to run away, so refusing to collect them until you need them is not a good option either.The people are finite too: once you run out, that's it. The game doesn't generate any people procedurally, and once your last person dies, that's game over. It accumulates to a rather off-putting thought: that the time you spent slacking off and exploring, or the hours spent making mistakes and trying to learn the various mechanics could cost you the game down the road. I don't think the game is that unforgiving in the end, but the thought is discouraging nonetheless.That kind of pressure can really work well in a roguelike game (e.g. Invisible Inc -- great game, by the way!), but State of Decay is too long, and doesn't have enough procedural generation to work on that level. While the economy of zombies is very much dynamic, and makes the world feel alive and dangerous, the missions are exactly the same every time you attempt them.So, despite the obvious brilliance of State of Decay, it's a tough title to recommend. I appreciate more as a piece of art than a game, and not because the graphics are especially pretty. It's that hardcore ideal that I hold zombie games up to, conveying both the intoxicating freedom and the unforgiving hopelessness of surviving in a zombie apocalypse. The problem is that it conveys it too well. I'm hoping that anyone who actually reads all of this will not be discouraged from buying and trying this game. Most gamers just want a game they can be entertained by, and on that basis alone, I can't really recommend State of Decay. But if, like me, you can appreciate an innovative, indie take on a tough formula, even if it can be unpleasant to play, I wholeheartedly recommend trying it out."
