76561198106616285,Not Recommended,329430,34718572,Posted: 3 September,all,Xor,"After finding that I enjoyed the base building aspects of Fallout 4, I thought I'd give another game that emphasizes this element a try, so I purchased State of Decay: Year One Survival Edition. I liked the focus on building your base and defending your group of survivors, collecting resources, and fixing stuff. I liked the ability to switch between characters and level them up. In fact, I was looking forward to that: a mix of multi-character RPGs and FPSs. Overall, however, my impression of the game is mostly negative.First of all, this is a ""permadeath"" game, which means that if one of your main characters dies, you can't restore a previous save and get them back. The developers and afficionados of the genre would call this a feature, and, for those people, it should be available, but it should also be possible to turn this off. Just tell the player that having a permament character death be part of the authentic survival experience, but offer the option to restore. With permadeath, your game play has to necessarily be very conservative, just like, you know, in real life. You can't experiment: What if I just rush in and start slashing? What if I enter via this door or that? Sure, but then you could lose the character you spent hours building up. Ugh.  Isn't the point of a sandbox to experiment?Second, the game mechanics are buggy. Zombies in walls, PC and NPC occupying the same space (e.g. when climbing ladder), awkward attack animation, ice-skater walking animation, etc. There are also nuisances that may well have been intentional, such as the inability to trade items with another player-controllable character or to drop items. Once you pick up an item, you either have to stash it at your base or destroy it. You can't put it back into a container you're looting or drop it on the ground for another payer-controllable character to pick up. Lots of things that the developers should've fixed for their Year One edition.Third, the player gets inundated with quests that don't have a clear sense of priority. This may be intentional or not, but it leads to a frustrating first-time experience. In most RPGs, you have a choice of when to accept side-quests; in SoD, tasks (problems) just keep getting added to your journal. Should you deal with the character who is sad or angry first, because they are causing morale to drop, or help some trapped survirors because Lily said, ""better hurry,"" or advance the story line via main quest, or ... ?Overall, the game is built on a great premise, but sloppy execution and adherence to the permadeath doctrine made it unenjoyable for me."
