,Not Recommended,329430,33325201,Posted: 6 July,all,PlagueRaven,"I really got into this game for the first couple of hours, but then it really started to annoy me, and here's why:1) The game acts, for whatever reason, as though it's an online tablet game running on a server, even when you're not playing. That means that stuff will happen even when you're not in game. Which means that neighbors die, survivors use supplies, and you basically get punished if you don't sit on your *** for days binge-playing this.What makes this worse is that most of the ""random events"" that the survivors tend to engage in all seem to be deliberately negative.Frank shot a gun inside! He could have killed someone! Morale decrease.Shelby is scared! She's a total bummer who brings everyone down! Morale decrease.Jack doesn't like zombies and he's grossed out so now he's mad at you for not talking to him about it. Morale decrease.So-and-so got food poisoning from canned food somehow! Morale decrease.The way to boost morale is to actively work for it (or by outpost defenses against hordes, it seems, but the increase is tiny), by engaging in missions or other positive events. This is a total PITA, because a bunch of negative crap can be waiting for you when you get back on the game, and you have to go out and get your morale back. Why do I even want it back at this point? My survivors are just going to act like jerks again when I'm gone and my neighbors are going to die.These survivors seem to need a lot of babysitting. You'd think people who survived this far into a zombie apocalypse would have bigger stones than this. They just act like a bunch of whiners. Suddenly the currently played character is their only hope despite surviving through this until now.2) I'm okay with the perma-death (kind of...), but what I don't like is how I died for the first time: basically getting stuck in a doorway while a zombie standing halfway through a floor kept knocking me down into another two zombies behind me, who grabbed me from behind. The combat controls don't help, either, as they're a little clunky. So the game basically gave me the middle finger in this instance, and I couldn't go back unless I started the game over, but I was already about four hours into it and didn't feel like starting the entire game over again.3) all the different types of ammo and variations of medications. I like the realism, but this makes it more frustrating to arrange your inventory properly and clogs up your storage lockers. It'd be fine if there was one type of weak medication and one type of powerful medication, and one of each ammo type/gun type to make inventory more manageable, because some ammo, despite being totally different, have very similar images applied to them. So you'll go to pick them up, only to find that they aren't the same that you're already carrying. You feel a little cheated, because you're missing out on extra meds that you just can't carry because you're carrying another type. If they're worried about you being over-supplied with meds, they can easily remedy this by slimming down the chances of you finding any while also omitting all the unnecessary different types.4) I'm confused by some of the directions the missions give me when it relates to morale issues (such as someone being ""freaked out"" or whatever). They imply that I need to go talk to that survivor to calm them down. I go inside the base to talk to them, but it only gives me the opportunity to ask them to accompany me outdoors. Maybe I'm an idiot, but I can't seem to figure out exactly how I'm supposed to help these people. Maybe I don't have to at all?5) The driving controls make me want to hang myself. I don't know if it's any better when using a controller, but on the keyboard, it's a nightmare.6) I asked one of the survivors to come fight with me. While in the middle of a mission, he said it was time for him to go home now, and he ran straight into a horde of zombies within a minute and nearly died. If I hadn't had the mind to chase after him and ""escort"" the idiot home, he would have been guts on the pavement. So now I feel like I have to go out alone, because my followers are too stupid to survive in a high-stakes environment by themselves.There are good things about the game. I like the immersion (although the story seems very meh), and I like getting to know various characters (even in the most bare-bones sense of the word), and I do greatly enjoy some of the survival aspects (going into abandoned homes and rummaging through stuff to find supplies). But the positives don't outweight the negatives for me right now.  I really, really want to enjoy this game, I really do. I was pumped for it, and I was getting into it at first. I might actually be more okay with it if there was a way to turn off activity happening when I'm not playing. If there was ever a mod or add-on or something for this, I'd continue playing it.Seriously, someone get on turning that crap off."
