76561198052354051,Not Recommended,329430,29876562,Posted: 12 February,all,Guy_Fleegman,"I don't know where to start with this game. Apparently there's no intro-- I start a new game, the scene opens and I'm standing by water being attacked by zombies. Not even time to get my bearings, adjust to the physics of the game, make any necessary changes, or even process a storyline. Following this my main character acts completely nonchalant about what's going on, apparently unbothered by either the zombies attacking him or, if he's unaware they're zombies, the fact that he just murdered three people.The controls are not good. The movement feels awkward, turns are awkward, the camera is also awkward. I suspect gunplay would not be particularly fun in this game and the melee (at least at the start) is mindless mashing.Following the very abrupt introduction (i.e. appearing with no context or character/story build-up whatsoever), I make my way to a nearby ranger cabin and am greeted by someone who acts like I know exactly what's happening. Here, take these supplies and head back out to secure the area! And I, seeming to lack interest in the background of this situation, unable to express shock or horror at the unfolding situation, agree to do this with no particular need to question this man.I head back out to explore the area, climbing a water tower to assess different points of interest. This is pretty cool and finally begins to ground me a bit. I manage to access the menu system (which, for some unknown reason, does not default to the Escape key but instead picks a random button on my mouse) and am fairly bombarded with information. It's not an excessive amount of stuff-- it seems they struck a good balance between depth and accessibility-- but it's still a lot to take in at once and with no real tutorial. I manage to access game controls and can finally fix the y-axis reverse and change some of the hotkeys.Following this I begin to explore and seek out quest locations. However, my minimap is not 'locked' but changes as my facing changes-- again, I can't comprehend why this was done. So I have a difficult time orienting myself in the pursuit of static locations. I also realize that the movement isn't getting much better, even after adjusting the camera sensitivity.I find a few cabins, beat down some deadites, and enter to see what appear to be items strewn all over. Yet the cabin is described as empty and there's nothing to loot. I noticed the same thing in the ranger station-- lots of goods lying around that can't be picked up. I find this strange and an immersion breaker.A few minutes later I realize that I am already bored and have no real interest in trying to adapt to the game's clunky controls, no real sense of world immersion (largely due to the horrible 'plop you in with no context'), and am getting no enjoyment whatsoever from the combat. I log out after about twenty minutes for the second time since I picked the game up, recalling that I had tried once to play, didn't enjoy it, but wanted to give it another chance.Now I know it's not a fluke. The game as a whole might be fun, and it might have been more acceptable before I got into the Fallout series, but at this point I just can't comprehend some fo the developer decisions or the lacklustre beginning-- which is generally among the most important parts of a game and should be polished quite a bit before release.Scoring this game would be difficult because I haven't given the breadth of it much of a chance. So I will say 5/10, but if you can get past the issues I've outlined here, or really, really love zombies, the system seems interesting enough to warrant a 7."
