76561198026800056,Recommended,329430,20260187,"Posted: 3 January, 2016",all,Karisse,"Bottom line up front: Think a less comical Dead Rising without the stun-locking psychopathes with more than one playable character, Left4Dead-style special infected and some Walking Dead scavenging. It's no flawless diamond, but it's FUN.Don't let the ""Mixed"" rating fool you. If you look up the original State of Decay (that's not longer available for purchase), you'll see it had plenty of people praising it. Most of the negative reviews for SoD seem to be original owners who were upset they bought the special edition and found it didn't offer much more than the original.The difficulty is sneaky, and I mean that in a good way, like when you try to sneak up on a lone zombie, only to realize (too late!) that there was a cluster of zombies standing just out of sight, or when you leap out of a window to make a quick get away, only to land right in the path of a zombie horde. The tension can ramp up quick, and a moment of carelessness can result in a deadly chase.Houses that aren't cleared every so often can get infested, leading to more freaks (special infected) and hordes wandering around (and even wind up attacking your home base). To compensate, you can build outposts, set traps and recruit more survivors to defend your home. It's a fun feature and it's nice to know you can create small pockets of (relative) safety.My rig isn't high end by any means (Laptop, 5th Gen. Intel Core i3, integrated HD graphics), so I have to run it on minimum graphics, but it rarely chugs. Occasionally, a zombie will be standing in a wall, or I'll swing endless at a zombie and the hits won't register until I dodge away (not sure if that's a graphic problem on my end or a bug). That's about the worst problem I've encountered in my 20 hours of gameplay.Give it a chance, especially if you can catch it on sale."
