76561197975310237,Recommended,329430,24531830,"Posted: 25 July, 2016",all,Terror,"The Good:- Endless hours of fun.- Incredibly terrifying moments when you truly believe that all is lost and there's no point in going on. (Which leads to one of the best achievements involving 1 grenade and many zombies *no spoilers*).- This is a fantastic game for virtual hoarders. (I've spent more time in cars than on foot, hooning around the map picking up rucksacks just to keep my influence in check *Influence is actually a currency in the game which you will need to build or use just about anything*).- A huge modding community which enables you to change the game to suit your own personal play style. (This is a must for any good apocolyptic sandbox).- Awesone game play.- Decent sound effects and music throughout.The Bad:- Yes, the graphics are outdated, even with the YOSE version (Year-One Survival Edition).- Lilly: Your Personal Assistant to ""The End Of The World"". She's an annoying woman. Does this sound familiar to all you SOD Veterans? ""Sounds like they're in a bad spot, maybe you should lend them a hand"". Yes, the character audio gets old VERY quickly. But thankfully to the Modding Community, you can shut her up.. PERMANENTLY.- Soul crushingly repetitive quests. Go here, fetch this, kill that and save this person from themself. Again, gets very old.. very quickly.- There are many elements to this game which fell short upon release, but again.. thanks the modding community, a lot of this game has been improved. More inventory slots in vehicles and the ability to slow down (control) behaviour of the zombies is a nice touch.The Horrible:- Lilly. You all know what I'm talking about. She sure as hell doesn't have to keep reminding me that time is short on EVERY single BLOODY mission. I'll get to it ALRIGHT?! It definitely makes freedom hard to bare when you're being constantly verbally carpet bombed by an incredibly up beat woman, who realistically does SFA towards helping humanity during the apocolypse.State Of Decay 2 has been confirmed:Is there anything they should incorporate to improve on the original game? Yes. Many things. Here are some of the main things that need to be improved:- Graphics, obviously.- Sound (character or otherwise). This includes and is not limited to character dialogue.- Music.- More quests. (And a lot more variety).- More vehicles. (Modding them would be great. Let us go all ""Dawn Of The Dead"" on the apocolypse, heavy plated shuttle busses for everyone!). Oh, and for the record.. there's a big difference between putting 6 rucksacks and 6 stacks of cofee in the back of a vehicle. I'd change the storage slots to a ""Weight Limit"". It makes more sense.- A lot more base customisation. There's no need to go Fallout 4 on the game, but at least give us some nice choices.- Weapon customisation. (And more melee weapons. Firearms too if they can.)- A larger playable area. The original mad from SOD is incredibly small compared to other modern sandboxes. Think: Day Z, on a much grander scale. Show us what Trumbull Valley really looks like.- A wider variety of buildings.- Possibly destructible environments as well.- And if the developers see fit to release a similar DLC like BD, go a bit harder on the density of zombies. I loved games like Dyling Light that made you really work to get where you needed to get to early on in the game. This made for an excellent challenge and a superb gaming experience all round.And most importantly.. Co-Operative play. MUST HAVE!Yes, I have much love for the Zombie Apocolypse. Many say it's being done to death. The truth is.. you can never have TOO MANY zombies. Bring on the end of the world.I'm really looking forward to SOD 2, and I'm hoping that Undead Labs knock one out of the ball park with it. Come on guys, don't dissapoint us! (No pressure)..Final thought: Would I recommend this game to anyone? You bet I would. 8/10 for State Of Decay - YOSE."
