,Recommended,329430,15688599,"Posted: 4 May, 2015",all,kmiklos,"Summary- If you don't own the original SoD, read on. The game is solid.- If you own the original SoD, this is just a minor update. Read below to find out what changed, and decide based on those and the current price tag.- Shortly after release, there are bugs. New ones. I trust they will be fixed soon.EDIT: A year later they seem to have gone. Either a fix or other changes in my PC got rid of them - for me, at least.ReviewThere are many negative reviews from people who actually like this game, just expected something more from this new release of their old favorite. To them: please remember that Steam users might decide on purchasing the game based on your reviews. Your review should be about the game, not the maker's way doing business. This game is solid. Some say this is the best single-player zombie apocalypse survival game in the Steam market. I agree with them.SoD:YOSE won't bring much for the owners of the original game though. These new features are:- High-res menu items and icons- Better lighting- One new car type (SUV)- Varied car paintings- One new hero- Many cool new weapons- Some new combat moves- Some new textures and 3D models (don't expect a lot!)- You can re-case ammo in the original campaign and 'Breakdown' too, not just in 'Lifeline'- You can find and use the military vehicle from 'Lifeline' in the original campaign and 'Breakdown' too- Some new bugs, hopefully to be fixed soon (nothing game breaking to me)About the game:SoD is a third person open-world zombie apocalypse survival game, unfortunately only single-player, where you can manage a small survivor community, build and upgrade base structures, and research new items for your ongoing combat against an unlimited zombie horde. The game has perma-death, some RPG elements, a wide variety of weapons and you can use the environment to fight the hordes too.The main campaign provides a mediocre story with a good atmosphere, and introduces you to the gameplay.'Breakdown' is a sandbox version of the main story - you play on the same map, without the storyline. You start in a random location, find and join a community, and then take on its management. When all resources were used up, or you are just bored, there is a broken RV you can fix and use to take a few key members of your community to another area. It will be the same map, with all resources respawned randomly, where you will start in a random point (from your broken down RV) and have to build up everything again. As you repeat the previous steps, the horde gets stronger and stronger, and you will receive new, stronger survivors to reinforce your team. This is my favorite game mode.'Lifeline' takes place on a new map, is more military-oriented and as such provides a different experience. It is a mixture of the previous two: there is some story, but you can decide to stay and continue saving people at an increased difficulty - with a global leaderboard.Would I recommend this game?- If you don't own the original, but like what you have read here, definitely.- If you own the original and like it, maybe. You won't get much extra, so decide based on what I wrote earlier. Or wait for a sale."
