76561198072027162,Recommended,329430,15643428,"Posted: 1 May, 2015",all,russonc,"State of Decay is a great mix of 3rd person zombie action and survival role playing.   Play is fairly open as to how you go about doing things (slow, stealthy, fighting everything in sight, etc).   To me, it feels more like being in a real situation as compared to some of the ""action only"" zombie games out.  Graphics are good, I much prefer the lighting in the YOSE version compared to the original, much better for my old eyes...  There is some clipping at times, nothing worse than I've seen in other games and nothing that bothered me.  I've not had any crashes (except vehicles..hehe).I highly recommend State of Decay.   If you don't have any version yet, go with YOSE version.   If you have the original but not the DLC from the original, this is still a good deal  (if you haven't played it to death).  If you have the original and the DLC you won't get as much out of this version so it's kind of iffy.    For me, the graphics make it worth getting, but others may just mod the original and they could certainly pass on this version.Overall a SOD is a nice addition to the genre and I hope to see more from UL."
76561197999735498,Recommended,329430,15646501,"Posted: 1 May, 2015",all,Belteshazzar,"In light of the bad reviews I've seen for this game, let me give a positive one.Disclaimer: I've only had a chance to play breakdown thus far, so I have no comments on the main game quest or on lifeline, but I expect like everything else they will be like the original.Summary:  If you enjoyed the original game, this version gives improved graphics and perhaps a tiny bit more gameplay stuff.  If you expected anything different than that, I don't know what to tell you.The game plays like the original game, because *gasp* it is the original game.  All that was promised was improved graphics and a few little tidbits to make the game more fun.  It's basically a textures overhaul mod you'd expect to see for Skyrim, except its official.I've heard complaints about the bugs, and all I can say is that they were neither better nor worse than the original game.  I'm guessing they were bugs that are driven by intricacies of the Cryengine version used be SOD, but that's just conjecture (it's all physics related and a few random crashes that honestly shouldn't happen, but I couldn't care less.)As for the improved graphics, I noticed a huge improvement.  Everything was far less dingy, and undead labs seriously toned up the lighting.  While I can sort of get the realism of not being able to see at night, I'm glad they fixed it because for me the game was virtually unplayable during 'night'; if you want to be unable to see for 50% of the game I would then of course recommend the original.They probably added new character traits, and definitely added new shirts and pants and hats.  This mixes up what sort of characters you will see and increases playability.  Similarly the vehicles were diversified and given new textures, which again makes for more replayability since there are more than 6 distinct cars in the valley.I did in fact notice the higher res textures.  The original was grainy as heck.  The menu and maps have been cleaned up significantly, which is really good.  I'm so glad they kept the physical journal interface (the game menus look like pages in a notebook) ====== very cool UI.  Plus you can now tell which item you have selected!In closing, the Year One edition is worth it if you liked the original game (or if you never played it, I suppose).  If you go in expecting a vastly different setting and feeling and a bug free game, then you'll be disappointed.Good luck, it's a brutal game."
